		<font class="clr bld">Wedding customs</font>
	</div>
	<div class="linesep"><img src="images/trans.gif" height="1" width="1" /></div>
	<center>
		<div class="rpanelinner padt10">
			<div class="normtxt clr lh16 tljust" style="padding-top:10px;">
			The Jains accord high value to the institution of marriage and do not believe in ostentatious traditions and customs. They like to hold simple and sober marriages sans pomp and show. The wedding is marked with rituals than tradition and several rituals are done to solemnize the marriage.<br /><br />
            <b>Pre-wedding rituals</b><br /><br />
            <b>Laghana Lekhan:</b><br />
            In this ritual, a small puja is held in the bride's house to determine the auspicious time or lagna or mahurat for the marriage. The officiating priest determines the auspicious time as close relatives and friends remain witness to the occasion. The lagna patrika or letter containing the wedding time is sent to the groom's home. <br /><br />
            <b>Sagai:</b><br />
            In this ritual, the groom performs the Vinakyantra at his residence. He wears the traditional Jain headgear and performs the Vinayakyantra puja. On completion of the puja, the bride's brother applies tilak on the groom's forehead and presents him with a gold chain, a ring, clothes, coconut, sweets and money. Thereafter, the lagna patrika is given to the groom. Usually, it is the priest, who reads out the lagna patrika. The groom  then seeks the elders' blessings.<br /><br />
            <b>Lagna Patrika Vachan:</b><br />
            The priest enquires the groom if he has done the Vinayakyantra puja. If he has done, the priest reads out the lagna patrika vachan at the groom's residence. The patrika is read out either on the day of engagement or at some auspicious time.<br /><br />
            <b>Mada Mandap:</b><br />
            After sagai, mada mandap is the next important pre-wedding ritual. Held in both the bride's and groom's house, it takes place one or two days prior to the wedding. All the rituals are performed by the priest.<br /><br />
            <b>Barati & Aarti:</b><br />
            The bride's brother receives the bridegroom's marriage procession in the Barati ritual and applies tilak on the groom's forehead. Also, he presents coconut, money, sweet and clothes to the groom. The bridegroom in return applies tika on the forehead of the bride's brother and gives him a coconut. Married ladies in the bride's house perform the traditional aarti. All the ladies get together and sing the Mangala Geet.<br /><br />
            <b>Wedding Rituals</b><br /><br />
            <b>Kanyavaran:</b><br />
            Kanyavaran marks the beginning of a Jain marriage ceremony. In the Kanyavaran or kanyapradan ceremony, the bride's parents or uncle places one rupee and twenty-five paise and some rice on the bride's right hand. Then, the bride is handed over to the groom. The bride's father makes a public announcement of the marriage for the favour of the assembled guests. While chanting the mantras, the priest pours water on the hands of the groom and bride thrice.<br />
            <b>Granthi Bandhan:</b><br />
            The Granthi Bandhan follows the Kanyavaran where the groom's shawl is tied to the bride's saree pallu. Married woman revel in tying this knot to the accompaniment of mantras. This ritual prepares the groom and the bride for 'phere', which is the next important ritual. <br />
            <b>Phere:</b><br />
            For the conduct this ritual, an auspicious time is selected days much ahead of the wedding and at the appointed hour, the the couple go round the sacred fire four times. The bride leads in the first round. Thereafter, they exchange their positions and take other three rounds around the havankund (sacred fire) to the accompanying recitation of Mahaveerakshak stoth in the background.<br /><br />
            <b>Mangal Geet:</b><br />
            The ladies sing and make merry during the phere after which the couple takes seven vows. After taking the vows, the bride is seated on the left side of groom. The bride is then called vamangi, or the better-half of her husband. Then both of them exchange garlands and the marriage is solemnized with the end of havan. <br /><br />
            <b>Post-wedding rituals</b><br /><br />
            <b>Ashirvada Ceremony:</b><br />
            In this ceremony, elders bless the newly married couple as they commence their new life together. <br /><br />
            <b>Sva Graha Aagamana:</b><br />
            The Sva Graha Aagamana pertains to welcoming the bride to her new home. It is the first custom after the newly wed couple reach their home.<br /><br />
            <b>Reception:</b><br />
            Though holding a reception is not a traditional ritual among Jains, it is performed in most of the Jain families. It serves as an occasion to formally introduce the bride to the rest of the family and relatives from groom's family.<br /><br />
            <b>Special Customs:</b><br />
            Jina Grahe Dhan Arpana tradition: This tradition appears to be specific to the Jains as both families give alms to the temple to express their gratitude for the successful solemnization of the marriage.<br />

